Evola tells a story of a secluded valley in the Andes, where all men were blind, due to an endemic disease that turned hereditary with years. A stranger came and was horrified at their condition, but they thought him mad and wanted to take his eyes away for causing his delusion.

When he escaped from them, he did not bemoan their sorry existence or sorrow over their illness, but climbed high up and up into the mountains and laughed looking down at their ghastly settlement from the peaks.

Thinking about Gene Wolfe saying you can sense the seasons changing even at sea. There are no leaves, but the currents change, waves get bigger, wind blows through the sand, seaweeds cycle, etc. Old seamen can probably tell the exact time of the year from the middle of an ocean.

An even more striking example is Dr. Ray Peat saying hibernating animals are able to know when winter comes even in laboratory conditions w/ constant light, no outside contact, etc., probably through radiation frequencies that change seasonally. (and are countred by hot springs.)
